text: Dimeric Pyranonaphthoquinones: Isolation, Bioactivity, and Synthetic Approaches Rodney A. Fernandes,*[a] Pradnya H. Patil,[a] and Dipali A. Chaudhari[a] Abstract: The dimeric pyranonaphthoquinones, “bis versions” of the naphtho[2,3-c]pyran-5,10-dione moiety, comprises a group of antibiotics that have been isolated from a variety of sources including plants, bacteria, fungi, and insects. This re- view discusses the known naturally occurring dimeric pyrano- naphthoquinones, their isolation and bioactivity, and synthetic The dimeric pyranonaphthoquinones, comprising a group of antibiotics, have been isolated from a variety of sources includ- ing plants, bacteria, fungi, and insects.[1] This review is about the diverse literature relating to the isolation and bioactivity of the dimeric pyranonaphthoquinones, as well as synthetic strate- gies directed towards them. Previous reviews have been fo- cused on monomeric molecules of this family, but until today [a] Department of Chemistry, Indian Institute of Technology Bombay, Eur. J. Org. Prof. Dr. Rodney A. Fernandes completed his Ph.D. in organic chemistry at the National Chemical Laboratory, Pune, India, under the guidance of Dr. Pradeep Kumar; postdoctoral research in Tohoku University, Japan, with Prof. Yoshinori Yamamoto; AvH fellow and then DFG postdoc- toral fellow at the University of Freiburg with Prof. Reinhard Brückner. He started independent research at the Instituto de Quimica, UNAM, Mexico City (Sep 2006–July 2007) and then joined the Department of Chemistry, Indian Institute of Technology Bombay, India (Assistant Professor), in August 2007 and became full Professor in May 2015. His research interest includes asymmetric synthesis, total synthesis, and development of synthetic methodologies. He was the recipient of the INSA medal for Young Scientists in Chemical Science in 2004 and has been a Fellow of Maharashtra Academy of Sciences from 2015. Dr. Pradnya H. Patil received her Master's degree in organic chemistry from North Maharashtra University, Jalgaon, India in 2009. She joined the group of Prof. Rodney A. Fernandes in the Department of Chemistry, Indian Institute of Technology Bombay, India, in July 2010 and obtained her Ph.D. degree in October 2015. Her doctoral research was mainly focused on the design and development of synthetic methodolo- gies and total synthesis of natural products. Miss Dipali A. Chaudhari obtained her Master's degree in organic chemistry from North Maharashtra University, Jalgaon, India, in 2007 and her M.Tech (industrial catalysis) from Cochin University of Science and Technology, Kerala (India), in 2011. She then joined the group of Prof. Rodney A. Fernandes in the Department of Chemistry, Indian Institute of Technology Bombay (India) for her doctoral studies in July 2012. She is working in the area of asymmetric synthesis and development of new synthetic methodologies. The major focus has been on the synthetic approaches adopted to complete the challenging total synthe- sis of the natural isolates and analogues.

no comprehensive review on the chemistry of the dimeric pyr- anonaphthoquinones has been documented. The structural framework common to these molecules basically consists of a bis-tricyclic system incorporating pyran, quinone, and benzene rings in a basic skeleton corresponding to the naphtho[2,3-c]- pyran-5,10-dione core structure A as shown in Figure 1.[2] An extension of structure A is a γ-lactone unit fused to a dihydro- pyran ring, defining B. It has been noticed that natural products containing structural unit B are quite common and are well- known for their bioactivity. Because their biosynthetic origin is from polyketide intermediates and acetate/malonate as starting units, the oxygen atom is typically incorporated at the C-2 posi- tion.[3–6] Some compounds of this family possess a carboxylic © 0000 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim acid side chain (form C), which might result from the ring open- ing of the γ-lactone. A number of them are of form D, in which the pyran ring has alkyl groups at C-1 and C-3 with distinct relative stereochemistry. Furthermore, both symmetrical and unsymmetrical dimerization of these monomeric units A–D through either a biaryl or a heteroatom linkage provides the dimeric pyranonaphthoquinones as an appreciably large group of molecules in this family of natural products. Figure 1. Monomeric units A–D of dimeric pyranonaphthoquinone natural products and selected examples of dimeric molecules (the numbering de- picted in A and B is commonly adopted and is used for consistency through- out this discussion). The dimeric pyranonaphthoquinones have attracted many researchers because of their associated vast and promising bio- activities, such as antitumor, antibacterial, and antiprotozoan activities.[2] They are generally active against a variety of Gram- positive bacteria, pathogenic fungi, and yeasts, and can also be Eur. J. Org. Chem. 0000, 0–0

used as alkylating agents upon bioreduction in a mode of ac- tion similar to that of antitumor drug mitomycin C.[7–9] Because of such properties and their intriguing structures this molecular class has attracted the attention of many synthetic organic chemists. The diversity of chemical structures found within the pyranonaphthoquinone family has encouraged a number of syntheses of monomers from this class of compounds; these have been reviewed earlier.[1a,2,10,11] However, synthetic efforts in the dimeric class of pyranonaphthoquinones are rather scarce, due to inherent challenges. Hence, many efforts have culminated in the synthesis of analogues or partial structures. The structural complexities are evident in the atropisomeric car- dinalin C 3 (1), the additional fused-γ-lactone-containing cris- amicin A (2), γ-actinorhodin (3), and phenocyclinone (4), the open-chain-acid-containing actinorhodin (5) and GTRI-BB (6), the thioether-linkage-containing BE-52440A (7) and frenolicin G (8), and more complex unsymmetrical dimers such as α- naphthocyclinone (9, Figure 1). The identification of potent anticancer activity in GTRI-BB (6), much higher than that of the marketed drug adriamycin (doxorubicin), is indicative of future potential in lead development through SAR studies based on compounds of this class. 2. Isolation and Bioactivity

The cardinalins are a series of dimeric pyranonaphthoquinones isolated from the purple-red fruit bodies of the New Zealand toadstool Dermocybe cardinalis.[12–14] These represent the first reports on the natural occurrence of dimeric quinones in higher-order fungi Basidiomycotina. Buchanan et al.[12] showed that the crude ethanolic extract of Dermocybe cardinalis exhibits significant cytotoxic activity against the P388 murine leukemia cell line (IC50 = 0.47 μg cm–3). Separation of this extract into its individual components yielded a colorless solid [cardinalin 1 (10)], two yellow quinones [cardinalin 2 (11) and cardinalin 3 (1)], and three red-purple pigments [cardinalin 4 (12), cardi- nalin 5 (13), and cardinalin 6 (14), Figure 2]. Subsequently, car- dinalins 8–16 (15–23),[14] unique pre-naphthoquinone dehydro dimers, were isolated from the same source – Dermocybe cardi- nalis.

The common core structural feature of all cardinalins is the presence of cis-1,3-dimethylpyran rings fused to their naphtho- quinone or hydroquinone nuclei. In the case of cardinalin 7 the absolute stereochemistry and folding pattern still remains undefined (so no structure is proposed). Cardinalin 1 (10) was obtained as colorless solid consisting of two octaketide sub- units[15,16] and has the most complex structure of all, with nine stereocenters and a stereogenic biaryl axis. It is the best exam- ple of a (cid:4)-hydronaphthoquinone chromophore, present in the B–C ring system. Cardinalin 2 (11) closely resembles 1, but it has ring B in the quinonoid form. Cardinalin 3 (1) is the simplest among them and is a symmetrical dimer of ventiloquinone L, (Rhamnaceae);[17] each pos- isolated from Ventilago goughii sesses a cis-1,3-dimethylpyran ring fused to a naphthoquinone nucleus. © 0000 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim Figure 2. The cardinalins 1–16 (the structure of cardinalin 7 is not defined). Because there are ortho substituents to the C8–C8′ biaryl bond, compounds 10, 11, and 1 showed no evidence of asym- metric doubling in either their 1H or their 13C NMR spectra. Hence, they occur as discrete atropisomers and from CD spec- tral study it is believed that they possess S axial chirality.

Cardinalin 4 (12) is a deep red microcrystalline solid con- taining a naphthazarin (5,8-dihydroxy-1,4-naphthoquinone)- chromophore[18] linked through a benzofuranoid bridge to a tetrahydropyranyl unit. The structure was established on the basis of NMR spectroscopic data and long-range NOE correla- tions. The C-4a′ epimer of 12 is known as cardinalin 5 (13). NMR spectroscopy revealed that the difference between 12 and 13 lay in the protons attached to the dimethylpyran ring F. From NOE calculations it was concluded that in 12 the EF ring junc- tion is trans-fused whereas in 13 it is cis-fused. Cardinalin 6 (14) is a red powder with an extended heptacy- clic bisquinone structure. It closely resembles 12 and 13 but has ring E in quinonoid form. The structures of the other cardinalins 8–16 (15–23) were deduced from spectroscopic data (1H and 13C NMR) and com- parison with the previously isolated cardinalins 1–6. The NMR spectroscopic data indicated 17 to be the C4a epimer of cardi- nalin 1 (10). Similarly, 20 and 21 are the C5′ formate esters of Eur. J. Org. Chem. 0000, 0–0 11 and 15, respectively. Cardinalins 15 (22) and 16 (23) were isolated from aged samples of 10 and 15, respectively.

The evaluation of cytotoxicity of the individual cardinalins 1– 6 (10–14 and 1) revealed that 12 and 13 show in vivo cytotoxic activity against murine leukemia P388 (12, IC50 = 0.28 and 13, IC50 = 0.40 μg cm–3).[12] It has been assumed that these com- pounds may be able to become transformed in vivo into α- methylene ketones (ortho-quinonoid structure) to act as Mich- ael acceptors to biological nucleophiles. Thus, the tetrahydropy- ran ring fused to the naphthoquinone part is necessary for the exhibition of bioactivity. Crisamicins were isolated from the microorganism RV-79–9-101, also known as Micromonospora purpureochromogenes subsp. halotolerans, obtained from a mud sample in the Philippines.[19–21] They show acid-base indicator properties (i.e., yellow-colored in acidic and purple in basic media). The crisamicins extract contained crisamicins A and B as the major bioactive compo- nents along with minor amounts of crisamicins C, D, and E.

The structure of crisamicin A (2) was determined by Ling and co-workers[22] and according to them it contains two pyran- fused lactones with C2 symmetry (Figure 3). It may be isolated as an amorphous orange powder or a crystalline needles, with no sharp melting points. According to mass spectroscopy, the molecular formula of 2 was deduced to be C32H22O12. However, 11 protons and 16 carbon atoms were observed in its 1H and 13C NMR spectra, respectively, which indicated that it has two identical halves. Its 1H NMR spectrum and its UV spectrum, with maxima at 215, 231, 267, and 435 nm, indicated the presence of a juglone-type chromophore.[23] An IR band at 1796 cm–1 confirmed the strained γ-lactone. The 1H NMR signals of 2 were identical with those of the monomer kalafungin.[24] The location of peri-hydroxy groups was deduced from derivatization of cris- amicin A (2), in which the lactone ring was opened in alkaline solution and transformed into a bis-acid. Treatment of the bis- acid with diazomethane yielded trimethyl derivative 24. The chemical shifts of the C4 OH and C-4′ OH protons appeared at δ = 2.47 and 2.70 ppm, respectively, suggesting different chem- ical environments for these two OH groups. Hence, NMR and IR data of trimethyl derivative 24 placed the phenolic hydroxy group at C-6 (as shown in 24, rather than at C-9 as in 25, Fig- ure 3). The ORD curve of crisamicin A showed a negative Cotton effect like that of nanaomycin D,[25] whereas kalafungin, its enantiomer, showed a positive Cotton effect. Thus, it was con- cluded that the absolute configuration of crisamicin A is (3aS,3a′S,5S,5′S,11bS,11b′S), which is the same as in nanaomy- cin D.

Crisamicin B is another component that runs close to 2 on TLC. The characterization of this was not executed because of its irreproducibility after fermentation. Crisamicin C (28) was also isolated from Micromonospora pur- pureochromogenes subsp. halotolerans along with crisami- cin A.[26] It is also an orange powder and is a C5a′, C11a′ epox- ide derivative of 2. The unsymmetrical dimeric epoxide struc- ture was confirmed by spectroscopic analysis and 13C labeled © 0000 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim Figure 3. The structures of crisamicins. feeding experiments.[26] Until today the determination of the exact stereochemistry of the epoxide moiety is elusive. Crisamicin A (2) derivatives [i.e., 1-hydroxycrisamicin A (26) and 9-hydroxycrisamicin A (27)] were produced by Micromonos- pora sp. SA246 and their structures have been elucidated.[27,28] Crisamicin A (2) is an excellent antitumor, antiviral, and im- munomodulatory[29] compound and shows good in vitro activ- ity against Gram-positive bacteria, with minimal inhibitory con- centrations ranging from 0.2 to 10 μg mL–1.[21] It also has inhibi- tory activity against B16 murine melanoma cell lines and antivi- ral activity against Herpes simplex virus and vesicular stomatitis viruses.[22] It exhibits little or no activity against Gram-negative bacteria, fungi, or the acid-fast Mycobacterium smegmatis. Cris- amicin C (28) also shows antimicrobial activity like crisamicin A, but it is more antibiotic in activity against Gram-positive bacte- ria.[26] The crisamicin derivatives 1-hydroxy- and 9-hydroxycris- amicin A possess antimicrobial activity against Gram-positive bacteria and inhibitory activity to the growth of some human cancer cell lines.[27,28]

The soil-dwelling bacterium Streptomyces coelicolor A3(2) pro- duces a red pigment – actinorhodin (5, Figure 4) – that shows pH indicator properties (bright blue in alkaline and red in acidic media).[30–32] The red pigment structure was assigned by exten- sive chemical degradation[33–35] and mass spectral studies.[36] Biosynthetic studies and 13C NMR analysis unequivocally deter- mined the point of dimerization.[37,38] The degradation of actin- orhodin dimethyl ester tetraacetate established the C8–C8′ link- age.[36] Actinorhodin (5) has also been found in cultures of Streptomyces lividans.[39] Oxidative degradation of actinorhodin diethyl ester with alkaline H2O2 provided triacid 29.[34] Compari- son of the ORD curves of 29 with those of (+)-(S)-lactic acid confirmed the absolute configuration of the stereogenic centers of 5 as (1R,1′R,3S,3′S).[36,40] The other actinorhodin congeners are α-actinorhodin (30), (cid:4)-actinorhodin (31), γ-actinorhodin (3), δ-actinorhodin (32), and ε-actinorhodin (33), all isolated from the same culture of the bacterium Streptomyces coelicolor (Figure 4).[41] Each con- tains oxygen atoms ortho to the biaryl linkage site. 1H and 13C Eur. J. Org. Chem. 0000, 0–0 Figure 4. The structures of actinorhodins.

NMR studies showed that actinorhodin and γ-actinorhodin are each dimeric, with two halves having the same structure and configuration and linked in a symmetrical fashion at C8–C8′ position.[36,39] ε-Actinorhodin (33) is a unsymmetrical dimer and possesses a monolactone-monoacid system analogous to that in 3. In δ-actinorhodin (32) the two halves are connected through a six-membered lactone system instead of the biaryl linkage. In all six congeners the dihydropyran ring has a quasi- axial methyl group at C-1 that is trans to an equatorial acetic acid side chain at C-3. This side chain is then able to participate in γ-lactone formation via a quinone-methide intermediate. A new analogue of actinorhodin – diepoxyactinorhodin (34) – was discovered from the same Streptomyces sp. by Imamura © 0000 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim and co-workers.[42] It is also a symmetrical dimer, like actinorho- din, with 4a,10a- and 4′a,10′a-diepoxy rings. Actinorhodin (5) shows activity against the Staphylococcus aureus bacteria found in the human respiratory tract and on the skin.[31] The antibacterial activity of diepoxyactinorhodin (34) against Bacillus subtilis, Escherichia coli, Pseudomonas putida, and S. aureus showed that it is similar to actinorhodin in activity toward Gram-positive bacteria (25–30 μg mL–1)[43] and not ac- tive towards Gram-negative bacteria or fungi.[42] 2d. Ventiloquinones and GTRI-BB

In 1991, Thomson and co-workers isolated a new dimeric ben- zisochromanquinone – ventiloquinone N (35) – along with monomeric compounds from the acetone extract of the root bark of Ventilago goughii (Figure 5).[17] From the NMR spectro- scopic data it was concluded that it has features of ventiloquin- ones L, C, and D.[44] Further, it was suggested that it is dimeric, possessing a possible linkage of the two fragments in the form either of epoxide 35′ or of oxetane 35. The former was ex- cluded on the basis of 13C NMR spectroscopic data favoring an oxetane, because the 13C-DEPT spectrum showed a ketal car- bon singlet at δ = 100.97 ppm. Similarly, the structure 35 ex- plains the anomalous resonance of one of the quinone carbonyl C atoms at δ = 175.54 ppm, due to deshielding effects of the ketal group at C-7′. Figure 5. The structure of ventiloquinone N. In 2002, Kim and co-workers reported the new isochromane- quinone antibiotic GTRI-BB (6) from the strain Micromonospora sp. SA246 (Figure 1).[45] It closely resembles crisamicin A, with an opened lactone as a methyl ester, and shows very promising cytotoxic activity on human tumor cell lines such as renal IC50 = 0.11 μg mL–1), and melanoma (UACC 62, IC50 = 0.08 μg mL–1). The inhibitory effect is much higher than that of the commer- cial anticancer drug adriamycin (doxorubicin). This indicates that a structure–activity relationship (SAR) study might result in enhancement of the cytotoxic efficacy of these compounds. It Eur. J. Org. Chem. 0000, 0–0 IC50 = 0.08 μg mL–1), colon (SW 620, also shows antimicrobial activity against Gram-positive bacteria such as B. subtilis IAM 1069. 2e. Protoaphins and Dactynaphins

In 1948, Todd and co-workers showed the effect of pH on color and fluorescence of several highly colored forms of the pig- ments collectively called protoaphins.[46] The yellow-colored pigments protoaphin-fb (36)[47] and protoaphin-sl (37)[48] were isolated from the hemolymph of bean aphid (Aphis fabae) and willow aphid (Tuberolachnus (Fig- ure 6).[47,48] These colored substances are hygroscopic, water- soluble, and acidic in nature. They can easily ionize at physio- logical pH to form violet-red anions that are responsible for the dark color of the insects. Figure 6. The structures of protoaphins. On the death of the insect, protoaphin-fb is rapidly con- verted by enzymatic action into the sugar-free yellow fluores- cent pigment xanthoaphin-fb (38, Scheme 1).[49] The latter loses a molecule of water and produces first the fluorescent orange chrysoaphin-fb (39), which then loses another molecule of water and is converted into the fluorescent carmine-red eryth- roaphin-fb (40), which is the stable end product of this se- quence of reactions.[50] The conversion of protoaphin-sl isomers is also similar (Scheme 1).

The structure of protoaphin-fb (36) was established through reductive cleavage with sodium dithionite to form a mixture of orange phenolic quinone E and colorless glucoside F (Scheme 2).[51] The structures of E and F were established by chemical[52] and spectroscopic studies.[52,53] From spectroscopic data (ultraviolet-visible, infrared, and NMR), quinone E was con- sidered undoubtedly a derivative of 5,7-dihydroxy-1,4-naphtho- quinone. Chemical tests on E yielded a monomethyl ether (di- azomethane), a yellow dimethyl ether (methyl iodide/silver ox- ide), and a leuco-tetramethyl ether (dimethyl sulfate). In addi- tion, in solution, the reddish-violet color of the monoanion of E changes to deep violet when it forms a dianion. The presence of a hydroxy group was confirmed by preparation of monoace- tates both from its dimethyl and from its leuco-tetramethyl © 0000 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim Scheme 1. Degradation of protoaphins. ether. The remainder of the structure of E was confirmed by chemical transformation. Mild chromic acid oxidation of E pro- duced D,D-(+)-dilactic acid (G),[54] of known absolute stereo- chemistry. Furthermore, E gave a positive iodoform test when treated with sodium hypoiodite despite the absence of a MeCH(OH)– group, which confirmed the presence of the benzo- quinone moiety. Thus the gross structure of E was established as that depicted in Scheme 2. Scheme 2. Reductive cleavage of protoaphin-fb. The stereochemistry was established through the close simi- larity of its proton spectrum to that of isoeleutherin,[34] the structure of which was established by synthesis. Later the struc- ture of E was confirmed by X-ray crystallography.[55]

The UV and IR absorption spectra of the second product F suggested that it contains a hydroxylated naphthalene moiety. Glucoside F was converted into sugar-free orange quinone H and sugar-containing quinone I when treated with Fremy's salt. Quinone I was converted into E on treatment with pigment- Eur. J. Org. Chem. 0000, 0–0 free enzyme extract from A. fabae. The quinone H was strongly acidic (pKa 3.8) and gave boroacetate (peri-OH group). The visi- ble, ultraviolet, and infrared spectra showed the structure to be identical with that of 2,5-dihydroxy-1,4-naphthoquinone. The combination of E and F provided the whole structure of proto- aphin-fb. Similarly, the combination of spectroscopic data and chemical properties of quinone and glucoside matched with the properties of protoaphin-fb. Reductive fission of protoaphin-sl (37) also provided gluco- side F along with another quinone E′ (not shown) that was isomeric with and similar to E. E′ also produced D,D-(+)-dilactic acid (G) on oxidative degradation, so the two quinones differ only in their configuration at the carbon atom bearing the hydroxy group. Quinone E′ contained relevant protons with cis configuration, which was confirmed by 1H NMR (J = 2.0 Hz), whereas these were trans in the case of E (J = 8.0 Hz). Therefore protaophins-fb (36) and -sl (37) are stereoisomers of each other and differ at one stereocenter.[51]

The chromophore of the erythroaphins was confirmed by a band at 1627 cm–1 in the IR spectra, the green color in alkaline solution, and the formation of purple complexes with boroace- tate and stannic acetate and mellitic acid on oxidation with nitric acid. Zinc dust fusion afforded an alkylated 1,12-benzper- ylene (identified from the UV), whereas a carbonyl peak at 1715 cm–1, together with a positive iodoform reaction, sug- gested the presence of nonconjugated acetyl group(s). Compar- ison of UV and visible spectra showed erythroaphins to be de- rivatives of 4,9-dihydroxyperylene-3,10-quinone.[56–58] Protoaphin-fb (36) was isolated from Galla Rhois[59] on treat- ment with pancreatic lipase and 3T3-L1 adipocytes. The biologi- cal screening of 36 showed potent inhibitory activity against pancreatic lipase, with IC50 values of (30.6 ± 2.4) μM. Pancreatic lipase is a well-known key enzyme in the absorption of dietary triglyceride. A new component – deoxyprotoaphin (41)[60] – has been obtained from Dactynotus species and is structurally similar to protoaphins except it lacks a 4-OH group (Figure 7). Mild cata- lytic hydrogenolysis of 41 gave deoxyquinone and glucoside similar to protoaphins. The structure of deoxyprotoaphin was established in a way similar to that used for the other proto- aphins.[51] Treatment of 41 with aqueous extracts of A. fabae gave chrysoaphin-fb (39), so it was assumed that the binaphthyl linkage and the absolute configuration of the naphthalenic halves were the same as in protoaphin-fb (36). Figure 7. Structure of deoxyprotoaphin. © 0000 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim

A different group of pigments called dactynaphins were iso- lated from the aphids Dactynotus jaceae L.[61] Like protoaphins and other aphid pigments, these compounds occur in living insects as glycosides. After the deaths of the insects, or on treat- ment with acid, they are transformed into mixtures of red and yellow isomeric interconvertible aglycones: rhododactynaphins- jc-1 (42) and xanthodactynaphins-jc-1 (43) as major compo- nents and rhododactynaphins-jc-2 (44) and xanthodactyna- phins-jc-2 (45) as minor ones (Figure 8). Both dactynaphins-jc- 1 and jc-2 have non-aromatic side chain like isoeleutherin[62] but the former has additional benzylic hydroxy group. Mild cat- alytic hydrogenation of the rhodo compounds afforded unsta- ble pale yellow quinols, so it was assumed that they are quin- ones. On the other hand, the xantho compounds were stable to mild reduction. Both rhodo and xantho compounds were found to exist in equilibrium; in aqueous media it shifts towards the xantho compounds. One of the two structures shown might represent the rhododactynaphins, but their close resemblance did not allow unequivocal assignment. Compounds 42 and 43 originated from acid hydrolysis of glycosidic protodactyna- phins-jc-1 (46), isolated from Dactynotus jaceae L.[63] The struc- tures of protorhododactynaphins-jc-1 (47) and -jc-2 (48) were elucidated by Cameron and co-workers.[60] Figure 8. Structures of dactynaphins. 2f. Pyran C–C and S-Bridged Dimeric Pyranonaphthoquinones

The Banyu Pharmaceutical Co., Ltd. isolated the two new di- meric pyranonaphthoquinones BE-52440A (7) and -B (49) from the mycelium of Streptomyces sp. A52440 (Figure 9).[64] This Streptomyces strain A52440 was collected in Ibaraki prefecture, Japan. They are dimers of nanaomycin, bridged with sulfur. The Eur. J. Org. Chem. 0000, 0–0 relative configurations of the three centers C1/C1′, C3/C3′, and C10a/C10a′ were determined,[64] but that of C4a and C4a′, as well as the absolute configuration, remained unknown. Re- cently, the structure has been deduced through total synthe- sis.[65] Figure 9. Structures of BE-52440A (7) and BE-52440B (49). BE-52440A (7) and -B (49) have antiproliferative effects in vitro against murine tumor cell lines such as P388 leukemia (IC50 = 6.1 and 1.1 μg mL–1, respectively) and colon 26 cell lines (IC50 = 2.1 and 3.4 μg mL–1, respectively) and also against hu- lines such as DLD-1 colon (IC50 = 0.47 and man tumor cell 0.69 μg mL–1, respectively), PC-13 lung (IC50 = 3.9 and 2.6 μg mL–1, respectively), and MKN-45 stomach cell lines (IC50 = 0.88 and 2.9 μg mL–1, respectively).[64] Their monomeric nanao- mycins exhibited antibacterial activity against Gram-positive bacteria and mycoplasma[66–69] but 7 and 49 did not show any antibacterial activity.

In 2002, De Kimpe and co-workers found a new pyranonaph- thoquinone – [(3α,3′α,4(cid:4),4′(cid:4))-3,3′]-dimethoxy-cis-[4,4′-bis- (3,4,5,10-tetrahydro-1H-naphtho[2,3-c]pyran)]-5,5′,10,10′- tetraone (50) from extracts of the roots of Pentas longiflora[70] (Rubiaceae), which is an important medicinal plant used as a cure for tapeworm, for itchy rashes, and for pimples,[71] as well as to treat scabies and the skin disease pityriasis versicolor (Fig- ure 10).[72,73] Its structure is composed of dimeric pyranonaph- thoquinones attached through a pyran–pyran C–C bond. This was established by extensive spectral analysis. Its biological properties are yet to be studied. Figure 10. Structures of tetraone 50 and frenolicin G. Thorson and co-workers recently identified the new S- bridged dimeric pyranonaphthoquinone frenolicin G[74] (8) along with the additional known compounds frenolicins C–F (Figure 10). Generally, frenolicins are characterized by the pres- © 0000 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim

ence of a pyranonaphthoquinone moiety with propyl substitu- tion at the C-1 position and are well-known for their antibacte- rial, antifungal, and antiprotozoal activities.[75–79] Frenolicin G (8) has a symmetrical dimer structure and contains a frenolicin core with a thioether bridge at the 4a-position. Scandium chlor- ide[80] (18 mg L–1), known for enhancement of metabolite pro- duction, was used during the fermentation of Streptomyces sp. RM-4–15, and this led to a marked improvement in the produc- tion of frenolicin G, deoxyfrenolicin,[76,78,81] and UCF 13.[82] Fre- nolicin G (8) was screened in a standard cancer cell line cytotox- icity assay against the human non-small-cell lung carcinoma A549 and was found to be inactive (IC50 > 80 μM). 2g. Uroleuconaphins and Cyclinones

In 2006, Tsunoda and co-workers[83] reported that the aphid Uroleuconnigro tubercalatum (Oliver), feeding on Solidago altis- sima L, produced two new red pigments named uroleucona- phins A1 (51) and B1 (52, Figure 11). Compound 52 is dimeric with C-15 units of quinone 53 and is the hydroxy derivative of 51. The structures and absolute configurations of 51 and 52 were determined by single-crystal X-ray analysis of deriva- tives.[83] The compounds possessed cytotoxicity against human promyelocytic leukemia HL-60 cells, with ED50 values of 45 μM and 20 μM, respectively.[84] Two years later, the same group iso- lated four yellowish pigments – uroleuconaphins A2a (54), A2b (55), B2a (56), and B2b (57) – which are minor components of the same aphid.[85] Compounds uroleuconaphin A2a (54) and B2a (55) are C10a epimers of uroleuconaphins A2b (56) and B2b (57), respectively. All compounds contained two C15 units of quinone 53 or a dehydroxy quinone unit linked through a 1,3- Figure 11. Structures of uroleuconaphins. Eur. J. Org. Chem. 0000, 0–0 dioxolane ring. Bioactivities of all uroleuconaphins are currently under evaluation in Tsunoda's laboratory.

A slightly more complex dimer – phenocyclinone (4)[86] – was isolated from the mycelium of Streptomyces coelicolor (Fig- ure 1). It resembles γ-actinorhodin (3), which was isolated from the same organism but contains a third aromatic ring. It is a derivative of the pentaphene ring system in that the pyran-γ- lactone unit is attached to a naphthazarin nucleus that can also be found in granaticin, fused either side of a methylbenzene moiety. It gives color reactions similar to those of binaphthaza- rin. Although all four hydroxy groups are chelated (νCO 1620 → 1672 cm–1 on acetylation) it surprisingly forms a tetra- methyl ether when treated with diazomethane. NMR study re- vealed that it has the same relative configuration at each end of the molecule and that the lactone rings are cis-fused to the adjacent heterocycle. The absolute stereochemistry at the asymmetric center is undetermined, however, and the choice between the four possible directions of annellation of the two dihydropyran rings is a tenuous one, based on some less than compelling biosynthetic arguments.[86]

The naphthocyclinones 9 and 58–63 were isolated for the first time by Zeeck and co-workers in 1974, from cultures of Streptomyces arenae, strain Tü 495 (Figure 12).[87] The structures elucidated by Zeeck's group showed that they were related to the general class of isochromonequinone antibiotics. Each mol- ecule has two different halves connected through two C–C bonds to form a bicyclo[3.2.1]octadienone skeleton, with one of the benzisochromane units modified to an aryl ketone moi- ety. α-Naphthocyclinone (9) was isolated as an orange dye.[87] The structure of α-naphthocyclinone was established on the basis of spectroscopic data[87] and chemical degradation.[87] CD spectra of the degraded products[88] obtained from 9 confirmed the absolute configuration of the stereogenic centers on the dihydropyran ring. Its structure was a combination of a 2,5,8- Figure 12. Structures of naphthocyclinones. © 0000 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim trihydroxy-1,4-naphthoquinone system with 3-hydroxybutyric acid at C-3 position and a 2-hydroxyarylketone moiety with a fused dihydropyran ring. These two halves of the molecule were connected through two C–C bonds. The red (cid:4)-naphthocycli- none (58) and its lactone derivative γ-naphthocyclinone (59) were also isolated with α-naphthocyclinone (9).[88] Spectro- scopic data and diazomethane degradation of 58 and 59 estab- lished that each half of the molecule contains a dihydropyran ring, with an extra fused lactone ring in 59.

The stereochemistry of these rings (1S,3R) was confirmed by the CD spectra of the degradation products. The position of the acetoxy group at C-6 was confirmed by reduction of the keto group at C-16 to an alcohol and NMR spectroscopy. X-ray crys- tallographic analysis[89] of 59 confirmed its structure, as well as the configuration of the central bicycle ring as (6R,15S). Later, three naphthocyclinones – (cid:4)-naphthocyclinone epoxide (60), (cid:4)- naphthocyclinone chlorohydrin (61), and δ-naphthocyclinone (62) – were isolated.[90] They each contain the (cid:4)-naphthocycli- none molecular skeleton, but the double bond at C-4a/C-10a has instead been converted into an epoxide or a chlorohydrin, or a hydroxy ketone system, respectively. γ-Isonaphthocyclin- one (63) was separated from the isomeric γ-naphthocyclinone (59) by the use of silica gel impregnated with L-(+)-tartaric acid. Examination of spectroscopic and CD data revealed the abso- lute configuration at all centers, which matches with 59 except in the case of the pyrano-γ-lactone ring, which is inverted. The bioactivities of some of the naphthocyclinones have been investigated. α-Naphthocyclinone (9) displayed no bioac- tivity whereas (cid:4)-58 and γ-59 were active against Gram-positive bacteria. Derivatives of these and other naphthocyclinones[90] were tested against Staphylococcus, Proteus sp., and E. coli, dis- playing marked activity in these trials. The dimeric pyranonapthoquinones pose different level of syn- thetic challenges, unlike the monomeric molecules. Total syn- theses only of a very few members have been completed, with most attempts having resulted in racemic and analogue synthe- sis. The syntheses are classified on the basis of the individual strategies implemented.

Laatsch[91] achieved the semisynthesis of an enantiomer of ac- tinorhodin – ent-actinorhodin (67) – from α-naphthocyclinone 9 (Scheme 3). Further degradation of 64 by treatment with diazomethane and monomethylation provided naphthol 65. Oxidative coupling of the monomer 65 by treat- ment with silver(I) oxide afforded the dimer 66, which upon oxidation with cerium ammonium nitrate (CAN) provided the dimer 67, which is ent-actinorhodin. By the known literature procedure reported by Kraus et al.,[93] the lactol 72 was treated with Et3SiH and CF3CO2H to give cis-ether 73, whereas the lactone ring of lactol 72 was cleaved by the same method of Kraus[93] to give an acid, which on treatment with diazomethane afforded ester 74. Double Furofuran Annulation Strategy

In 1998 Brimble and co-workers artfully synthesized the dimeric pyranonaphthoquinones 82 and 83, the structures of which are closely related to that of 5, for the first time (Scheme 5).[96] Earlier, monomeric pyranonaphthoquinones such as kalafun- gin,[97] nanaomycin A, frenolicin B[98] and arizonin C1[99] had been synthesized by them by use of the furofuran annulation strategy. They extended this strategy to the synthesis of dimer molecules. The work commenced with the synthesis of dimer 77 for the double furofuran annulation. “One-pot” Suzuki–Miya- ura homocoupling[100] was attempted with bromonaphthol 76, which was treated with PdCl2(dppf ) as catalyst and diboronpin- acolate to give dimeric acetylnaphthol in 53 % yield. On CAN oxidation this provided the bis-naphthoquinone 77. A subse- quent Diels–Alder reaction between 70 and 77 in acetonitrile at 0 °C resulted in bis-endo adducts, which underwent fragmen- tation to provide a 1:1 inseparable diastereomeric mixture of furonaphthofurans 78 and 79. The unstable mixture of 78 and 79 was further treated for the double oxidative rearrange- ment[92b,99,101] with CAN to afford an inseparable 1:1 mixture of bis-lactols 80 and 81. Hydrogenation of the hemiacetals and same-pot hydrogenolysis of the γ-lactone units of 80 and 81 over Pd/C resulted in the carboxylic acids. These were further treated with an ethereal solution of diazomethane to furnish a 1:1 mixture of bis-methyl esters 82 and 83. The structures of 82 and 83 were assigned by analogy to the monomeric mol- ecule 75 (Scheme 4). Thus, 82 and 83 are closely related to the bis-methyl ester of actinorhodin.

The second strategy was based on Stille coupling[103] be- tween 89 (prepared from 85) and vinyl stannanes 90 to provide an enol ether to be hydrolyzed to 91. Unfortunately, however, the methylation of 88 gave 89 in only 39 % yield. Further Stille coupling between 89 and 90 provided the enol ether, which Eur. J. Org. Chem. 0000, 0–0 Scheme 5. In continuation of their work on dimeric molecules, in 2003 Brimble and co-workers classically extended the furofuran an- nulation strategy to crisamicin A (2, Scheme 7).[104] Considering the biaryl linkage in 2 to be different from that in 5 they at- tempted the synthesis of regioisomeric bisacetyl compound 100 (regioisomer to 86, Scheme 6). They adopted the Suzuki– Miyaura coupling for the construction of bis-naphthalene com- pounds 96–98 from the known triflates 92–94, respectively, for coupling with 95.[105] They observed that the OH-protecting group played an important role in the coupling reaction. Whereas acetyl protection did not work (compound 96), the TBS compound 93 gave a lower yield of 97. The naphthyl com- pound 94, with isopropyl as protecting group, gave a good yield of 98. The oxidation of 98 to bis-naphthoquinone 99, fol- lowed by double selective reductive acylation and finally meth- ylation, furnished the bis-acetate 100. The double Fries rear- ranged product of 100 would be bis-acetylnaphthalene 101, but several efforts directed towards this conversion with use of various conditions such as BF3, AlCl3, and Sc(OTf )3 were unsuc- cessful. In 2008, Brimble and co-workers completed the first enantiose- lective synthesis (Scheme 9) of the core structure of cardinalin 3 (1).[107] The key steps involved were Hauser–Kraus annula- tion[108,109] and late-stage Suzuki–Miyaura homocoupling of the monomer. The cyanophthalide annulation precursor 109 was prepared from 6-methoxyphthalide (108)[110] in six steps. The next partner α,(cid:4)-unsaturated ketone 110 was synthesized from commercially available ethyl acetoacetate in four steps.[111] The key Hauser–Kraus annulation step of 109 with 110 proceeded smoothly in the presence of tBuOK to give the naphthoquin- one, which was methylated to afford the functionalized naphth- alene 111 in good yield. Facile debenzylation of 111 (H2, Pd/C) delivered a phenol that underwent smooth triflate formation to give 112. The next step, Suzuki–Miyaura homocoupling of 112, was achieved in one-pot fashion after careful optimization. The reaction of triflate 112 was carried out under microwave irradia- tion (300 W, 150 °C) in the presence of 95 and Pd(dppf )Cl2- dppf catalyst for 1 h to furnish homocoupled product 113. Ando and co-workers developed a method for the synthesis of the bicyclo[3.2.1]octadienone scaffold present in (cid:4)-naphthocy- clinone (58) based on a thiolate-mediated reductive cyclization strategy.[148] Saturated bisenones 204 or 205 reacted with eth- ane-1,2-dithiol (excess) and NaH to provide keto–enone inter- mediates 206 or 207, respectively (Scheme 22). In this reaction, the reagent EDT-Na, generated in situ from 1,2-ethanedithiol and NaH, served as two-electron reductant, which is a putative species for the mechanism. It is effective because of its weaker basicity and serves as a good nucleophile for 1,4-addition. The reaction consists of two stages. The first stage begins with 1,4- addition of EDT-Na to bisenone 204 or 205 to generate an enol- ate, which after rearrangement provides keto–enone intermedi- ate 206 or 207, respectively. In conclusion, the dimeric family of pyranonaphthoquinone an- tibiotics represents an interesting family of biologically active natural products. This review has provided a comprehensive summary of the isolation, bioactivity, and synthesis of this class of dimeric pyranonaphthoquinones. Because of the complex structures of these compounds and related intrinsic difficulties, many synthetic attempts have been restricted to the core struc- tures and closely related analogues, with a few being racemic syntheses. These compounds are at the center of attraction for many researchers because of their unique properties, such as the pH indicator properties of crisamicins and actinorhodins, the anticancer activities of GTRI BB, BE-52440A/B, etc. In addi- tion to dimeric pyranonaphthoquinones such as crisamicins, ac- tinorhodins, and cardinalins, similar compounds in this group – namely protoaphins, dactynaphins, and naphthocyclinones – are less explored and their synthesis is yet to be achieved. Most of these compounds, such as crisamicin, actinorhodin, etc., are biosynthesized via polyketide intermediates. There is vast ongo- ing research into the biosynthesis of actinorhodins with the aid of genetic engineering. A few dimeric compounds are atropiso- mers and pose greater difficulty in total synthesis. However, the Brimble and the Fernandes groups have successfully achieved the synthesis of core structures of these family members in chi- ral forms. © 0000 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co.
